#### Issue details

Type information of serialized map is preserved after the map is deserialized.
#### Reproduction steps/code

```

public class TestObject{

    private String id = "id";
    private Map<String, String> map = new HashMap<>();

    TestObject(){
        map.put("a", "b");
        map.put("c", "d");
    }

    public String getId() {
        return id;
    }

    public void setId(String id) {
        this.id = id;
    }

    public Map<String, String> getMap() {
        return map;
    }

    public void setMap(Map<String, String> map) {
        this.map = map;
    }
}

```

```

public class JsonJavaTest {
    public static void test(){

        Json json = new Json();
        json.setUsePrototypes(false);
        json.setIgnoreUnknownFields(true);
        json.setOutputType(JsonWriter.OutputType.json);

        String jsonStr = json.prettyPrint(new TestObject());
        // Expecting 2 items in map
        TestObject testObj = json.fromJson(TestObject.class, jsonStr);

        for(Map.Entry<String, String> entry : testObj.getMap().entrySet()){
            System.out.println(entry.getKey() + " : " + entry.getValue());
        }
    }
}
```

In the above example the expected result would be:

> a : b
> c : d

But deserialization produces

> a : b
> c : d
> class : java.util.HashMap
